ing the theatre, modernist adaptations of puppet theatre, the Faust legend and its vogue in early twentieth-century Russia, and the nineteenth-century panorama. The book reveals that what binds these otherwise disparate phenomena together is a shared impatience with history and a corresponding desire to appropriate urban space. Illuminating the deeper meanings in these revived archaic forms, Staging the Absolute shows how pervasive the interest in disrupting history was in the Russian modern era.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aCity planningzSoviet Union. 0aFestivalszSoviet Union. 0aRussian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aTheater and societyzSoviet Union. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  aRussia’s modern era.  aSoviet culture.  aSoviet history.  aSoviet ritual.  aStalin.  aStalinist ritual.  aculture of space.  aeschatology.  aintervention.  amodern Russian history.  apanoramas.  apropaganda.  apuppet theatre.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023 Englishz978311131918608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studies 2023z978311131826408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079737440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148755181040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487551810423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487551810/original  a978-3-11-079737-4  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  a978-3-11-131826-4  EBOOK PACKAGE Literary Studie